  "raw_html": "<button type='button' role='link' class='btn btn-link p-0 text-start' id='link_2' aria-label=\" Directorate of Revenue Intelligence versus Raj Kumar Arora & Ors. pdf\"  class='noToken' href='#' onclick=javascript:open_pdf('2','2025','2025_4_835_984','2025INSC498'); ><font size='4'> <strong>DIRECTORATE OF REVENUE INTELLIGENCE<span class='fst-italic'> versus </span>RAJ KUMAR ARORA & ORS. </strong>- <span class='escrText'>[2025] 4 S.C.R. 835</span><span class='ncDisplay'>2025 INSC 498</span><input type='hidden' id='cnr' value=ESCR010004882025></button></font><br><strong>Coram : J.B. PARDIWALA<sup style=\"color: #268e97;font-size: 22px;top: 0;\" class=\"tooltip-sup\" data-tooltip=\"Author\">*</sup>, MANOJ MISRA</strong><br> Issue for Consideration Issue arose whether an offence u/s.8(c) of the NDPS Act could be said to have been made out when an accused &ldquo;deals with&rdquo; psychotropic substances mentioned in the Schedule to the NDPS Act but not figuring in Schedule I of the Rules thereunder; whether the case must operate with prospective effect; and that once, charge has been framed by a competent court u/s.228 CrPC, can an accused thereafter seek for discharge/deletion of a particular offence from the charge u/s.216 CrPC. Headnotes&dagger; Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances<br><strong class='caseDetailsTD' ><span style='color:#212F3D' > Decision Date :</span><font color='green'> 17-04-2025</font><span style='color:#212F3D' > | Case No :</span><font color='green'> CRIMINAL APPEAL No. 1319/2013</font><span style='color:#212F3D' > | Disposal Nature :</span><font color='green'> Appeal(s) allowed</font>   <span style='color:#212F3D' > |  Bench :</span><font color='green'> 2 Judges</font></strong><div class='row my-1 mt-2 border bg-light'><div class='col-auto'><a href='#' class='btn btn-outline-secondary btn-sm my-1' onclick=open_splitview('2','2025','2025_4_835_984','2025INSC498','S')><i <i class='fas fa-columns me-2'></i>Split view</a></div><di